{
  "doc_id": "46882",
  "text": "Raman spectroscopy, which is based on vibrational spectroscopic techniques, is used to derive the chemical structure of substances [CITATION_1] . Most of the photons of incident light that strike a given molecule are elastically scattered with the 2 BioMed Research International same energy, but a small amount of photons (only 1 per 10 million) are inelastically scattered with different vibrational frequencies [CITATION_2] . This vibrational shift, which is manifested as a wavenumber shift or Raman shift, is a characteristic of specific molecules or chemical bonds and thus can be used to provide structural information on the targeted materials [CITATION_3] .",
